[3] Indonesia - WHO update 3; and additional confirmed case
Date: Mon 13 Feb 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Mon 13 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/JAK168495.htm>

Indonesia: 26th Case of Avian Influenza Confirmed
-----------------------------------------------
An Indonesian source said on Mon 13 Feb 2006 that the World Health
Organization has confirmed the country's 26th human case of bird flu,
while a Minister said infections of the virus in poultry must be
reported faster. Hariadi Wibisono, Director of Control of
Animal-borne Diseases at the ministry, said a WHO-recognized
laboratory in Hong Kong had confirmed a November 2005 case in which
the patient survived. "It was an old case, but we only recently
received the confirmation. He was admitted on 25 Nov 2005 but became
well again," Wibisono told Reuters, adding the man in question was
from Central Java province.
Indonesia, the world's 4th most populous country, has reported 18
human deaths from avian flu that have been confirmed by the WHO.
Local tests also showed a 23-year-old man died of bird flu on Friday
[10 Feb 2006], and tissue samples have been sent to the same Hong
Kong laboratory. [If confirmed, the avian influenza infection total
will become 27 and the number of deaths 19. - Mod.CP]
7 of the confirmed Indonesian fatalities have been in 2006, making
Indonesia the country with the most bird flu deaths so far this year.
While the virus mostly affects birds, the H5N1 strain of avian flu
has killed at least 90 people in 7 countries since 2003, according to the WHO.
While the virus remains hard for humans to catch from birds, experts
fear the virus will mutate to become easily passed between humans,
triggering a pandemic. The highly pathogenic strain of bird flu has
affected birds in 2/3rds of the provinces in Indonesia, an
archipelago of about 17 000 islands and 220 million people.
Agriculture Minister Anton Apriyantono said the reporting of possible
bird flu cases among fowl needs to be quicker. "We will repair the
reporting system, which so far has often been late. Frequently, the
media reports are faster than the reports from the ministry's own
team," he told reporters.
"There is an increase in the intensity of bird flu cases in several
areas in West Java," he said. Indonesia has millions of chickens and
ducks, many in yards of rural or urban homes, making it likely more
humans will become infected with the virus. For financial, social and
political reasons, Indonesia has been reluctant to undertake the mass
culling of fowl seen in some other countries, concentrating instead
on selective culling, and on public education and hygiene measures
aimed at prevention.
--
