[5] Greece - 2 people quarantined after contact with swans
Date: Mon 13 Feb 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Mon 13 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L13695264.htm>

Greece: 2 People Placed in Quarantine
---------------------------------------------
The Greek authorities said on Mon 13 Feb 2006 that 2 people had been
placed in quarantine pending the results of tests for possible avian
influenza, just 2 days after confirming the disease in 3 dead swans.
In both cases, initial tests have been negative, but the results of a
2nd round of tests are expected in the next one to 2 days, officials
said. "The procedure now requires that the 2 be placed under
quarantine," Panayiotis Efstathiou, head of the government
coordinating committee on bird flu, told Greek radio.
The 1st case involves a 15-year-old boy who came into contact with a
swan 9 days ago and showed flu-like symptoms. The 2nd was a
29-year-old hunter who killed 3 wild ducks a week ago. Both are in
quarantine in separate hospitals in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki, close to where the initial cases of H5N1 bird flu were
found last week [2nd week February 2006].
Last week [2nd week February 2006], the deadly strain of the bird flu
virus was found in 3 wild swans, while tests are now being conducted
on a wild goose from the Aegean island of Skyros.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The A/H5N1 avian influenza virus has killed at least 88 people in
Asia and the Middle East since early 2003, but there have been no
authenticated reports of human cases of avian influenza further west
than Turkey and none in countries of the European Union. All cases of
avian influenza in humans have been associated with food preparation
and consumption of diseased poultry, or proximity to poultry and pet
birds. So far, no human cases have been attributed to contact with
free-living species of birds. - Mod.CP]
